// Śaṅkara (Advaita) commentary position summaries — chapters 1–6.
// Paraphrase-quality summaries of Ādi Śaṅkara's bhāṣya readings, NOT
// direct quotations. Audit and tighten over time.
export const SHANKARA_PART_1 = {
  // ===================== Chapter 1 (47 verses) =====================
  '1.1': "Śaṅkara's bhāṣya proper opens with the upodghāta (introduction), not 1.1. He treats the first chapter as setting up Arjuna's शोक-मोह (grief and delusion); धर्मक्षेत्रे–कुरुक्षेत्रे frame the field as both literal battlefield and dharmic test where the Self's true nature must be discriminated.",
  '1.2': "The narrative shift to Sañjaya begins the report-frame. Śaṅkara generally lets the first chapter run as descriptive context, withholding heavy commentary because the philosophical teaching only begins once Arjuna's delusion is fully exhibited.",
  '1.3': "Duryodhana points out the Pāṇḍava array. Śaṅkara reads chapter 1 minimally; the assembly of armies establishes the व्यावहारिक surface that Krishna will eventually puncture by pointing to the unchanging Self.",
  '1.4': "Listing of warriors. Śaṅkara takes such verses as scenic setup and does not gloss them at length, since their function is to build up to Arjuna's collapse, which is what the bhāṣya truly engages with.",
  '1.5': "More names of allies. The bhāṣya passes over such enumerations; Śaṅkara's interest sharpens only where doctrinal questions arise.",
  '1.6': "Continued enumeration of Pāṇḍava-side heroes. Śaṅkara does not comment in detail; the verse's role is to magnify the stakes that will trigger Arjuna's विषाद.",
  '1.7': "Duryodhana now lists his own commanders. Śaṅkara skips elaboration, reserving exegesis for verses that bear directly on ज्ञान or कर्मयोग.",
  '1.8': "More Kaurava-side names. The bhāṣya remains silent here; it is not Śaṅkara's method to allegorise every name in chapter 1.",
  '1.9': "Many warriors ready to die for Duryodhana. Śaṅkara passes through; the verse contributes to the atmosphere of imminent loss that produces Arjuna's grief.",
  '1.10': "Bhīṣma's army called अपर्याप्त, Bhīma's पर्याप्त. Śaṅkara does not enter the अपर्याप्त/पर्याप्त controversy; the upodghāta has already declared that the chapter's pedagogical purpose is to display delusion, not to settle tactical readings.",
  '1.11': "Duryodhana orders protection of Bhīṣma. Śaṅkara does not gloss; descriptive material.",
  '1.12': "Bhīṣma blows his conch to cheer Duryodhana. Śaṅkara passes over.",
  '1.13': "The cacophony of conches and drums. The bhāṣya is silent; the noise is part of the dramatic pressure on Arjuna.",
  '1.14': "Krishna and Arjuna in the great chariot, blowing divine conches. Śaṅkara does not allegorise the chariot here, though the Kaṭha Upaniṣad image is obviously available.",
  '1.15': "Names of the conches blown by Krishna, Arjuna, Bhīma. Śaṅkara passes over.",
  '1.16': "Yudhiṣṭhira, Nakula, Sahadeva blow their conches. No comment in the bhāṣya.",
  '1.17': "Further enumeration of conch-blowers. Śaṅkara does not gloss.",
  '1.18': "All the conches make a tumultuous sound. Descriptive verse, not commented on.",
  '1.19': "The sound shatters the hearts of Dhṛtarāṣṭra's sons. Śaṅkara passes over; pure scene-setting.",
  '1.20': "Arjuna sees the army arrayed and lifts his bow. Śaṅkara begins to take more interest because Arjuna's perception is what triggers the breakdown that the entire teaching answers.",
  '1.21': "Arjuna asks Krishna to place his chariot between the armies. Śaṅkara reads this as the prelude to seeing kinsmen, which will produce the delusion (मोह) the Gītā exists to remove.",
  '1.22': "Arjuna wishes to inspect those eager to fight. The verse sets up the moment of recognition; Śaṅkara reserves analysis for when grief actually breaks out.",
  '1.23': "Arjuna wants to see who has come to support Duryodhana. Śaṅkara does not gloss.",
  '1.24': "Sañjaya reports Krishna placing the chariot between the armies. No bhāṣya.",
  '1.25': "Krishna says, 'Behold these Kurus assembled.' Śaṅkara notes that Krishna's neutral phrasing — पश्य एतान् — sets the trap: Arjuna will see them as kinsmen rather than as upholders of adharma.",
  '1.26': "Arjuna sees fathers, grandfathers, teachers, uncles, brothers, sons, grandsons, friends in both armies. Śaṅkara identifies this as the inception of स्नेह-moha (clinging affection masquerading as compassion); his upodghāta has already explained that this is the precise condition the Gītā cures.",
  '1.27': "Overcome with deep compassion (कृपया परयाविष्टः), Arjuna laments. Śaṅkara reads this 'compassion' as defective — a mixture of शोक and मोह, not true दया, because it is rooted in identification with the body and its relations.",
  '1.28': "Arjuna's limbs slacken, mouth dries, body trembles. Śaṅkara takes the physical symptoms as evidence that grief has overpowered विवेक: the senses obey delusion.",
  '1.29': "Hair stands on end, Gāṇḍīva slips, skin burns. The collapse of the body in grief shows Arjuna's identification with the kṣetra (field) rather than the kṣetrajña (knower).",
  '1.30': "Arjuna cannot stand; his mind reels. Śaṅkara: this is the very state — शोकमोह — which only आत्मज्ञान can dispel; medicine other than knowledge will not cure it.",
  '1.31': "Arjuna sees ill omens and questions the value of victory. Śaṅkara notes the inversion: the warrior who came to fight now reasons against fighting because his attachment has been activated.",
  '1.32': "Arjuna says he does not desire victory, kingdom, or pleasures. Śaṅkara observes that this looks like vairāgya but is in fact आसक्ति in disguise — renunciation born of grief, not of विवेक.",
  '1.33': "Those for whose sake we want kingdom and pleasures stand here ready to die. Śaṅkara: Arjuna's logic is governed by sambandha (relations), the very illusion the teaching will dismantle.",
  '1.34': "Teachers, fathers, sons, grandfathers — Arjuna lists relations he refuses to kill. Śaṅkara reads the list as the catalogue of attachments by which the jīva mistakes itself for a social being.",
  '1.35': "Arjuna will not slay them even for the three worlds, let alone earth. The hyperbole, for Śaṅkara, exposes the depth of moha; it is precisely such 'noble' refusals that क्षात्रधर्म exists to override.",
  '1.36': "Arjuna asks what joy can come from killing Dhṛtarāṣṭra's sons. Śaṅkara: the question presupposes that joy and sorrow are real properties of the Self, which the teaching will deny.",
  '1.37': "He says killing kinsmen would be sin (पाप), so they should not kill. Śaṅkara flags this as a misuse of dharma reasoning — Arjuna invokes scriptural categories to justify what is actually grief-driven flight.",
  '1.38': "Even if the Kauravas, blinded by greed, see no fault in destroying family, we who see it should desist. Śaṅkara reads this as Arjuna setting himself up as the moral one — a subtle अहंकार hidden inside renunciation.",
  '1.39': "He invokes कुलक्षय (destruction of family) as a known evil. Śaṅkara does not deny that कुलक्षय is regrettable in व्यावहारिक terms; the point is that Arjuna's duty is determined by his स्वधर्म, not by such consequentialism.",
  '1.40': "Family destruction, says Arjuna, leads to loss of dharma; with dharma lost, अधर्म overcomes the family. Śaṅkara: the chain of reasoning is conventionally correct but mis-applied — Arjuna is not the agent who would destroy dharma; abandoning स्वधर्म would be.",
  '1.41': "With adharma rising, women become corrupt; mixing of varṇas (वर्णसंकर) follows. Śaṅkara takes this in its smṛti sense as a real social concern but notes that Arjuna's invocation of it is rationalisation, not reasoning.",
  '1.42': "Varṇa-mixing drags family and destroyers of family to hell; ancestors fall, deprived of piṇḍa-water offerings. Śaṅkara accepts the doctrine of pitṛ-rites within व्यवहार but observes that Arjuna's argument is selectively deployed.",
  '1.43': "By such faults of family-destroyers, eternal jāti-dharma and kula-dharma are uprooted. Śaṅkara: Arjuna here speaks like a śāstric authority; the irony is that he is not in the position of authority to renounce his स्वधर्म on these grounds.",
  '1.44': "Those whose kula-dharma is destroyed dwell in hell — so it is heard (अनुश्रुश्रुम). Śaṅkara lets the smṛti citation stand; his quarrel is not with the citation but with Arjuna's misapplication of it.",
  '1.45': "Arjuna says, 'Alas, we are about to commit a great sin in our greed for the pleasures of kingdom.' Śaṅkara: this self-accusation is the climax of moha — Arjuna assumes that he and his kin are the ultimate doers, the very assumption the teaching will dissolve.",
  '1.46': "Better that the armed Kauravas slay me unarmed and unresisting in battle. Śaṅkara reads this surrender as defective vairāgya: the words of renunciation, the substance of grief.",
  '1.47': "Arjuna casts down bow and arrows and sits in the chariot, mind overwhelmed by grief. Śaṅkara: this is the precise condition (शोकसंविग्नमानसः) that the entire Gītā exists to remedy; chapter 1 ends with the disease fully exhibited so that chapters 2 onward can administer the cure of आत्मज्ञान.",

  // ===================== Chapter 2 (72 verses) =====================
  '2.1': "Sañjaya describes Arjuna as overpowered by pity, eyes filled with tears, despondent. Śaṅkara identifies this state — कृपया, अश्रुपूर्णाकुलेक्षणम्, विषीदन्तम् — as शोक-मोह arising from mistaken identification of the Self with body, kin, and role; he will say the cure is solely आत्मज्ञान.",
  '2.2': "Krishna asks where this अनार्यजुष्ट dejection has come from. Śaṅkara: Krishna's mild rebuke signals that this collapse is incompatible with स्वर्ग, fame, and most importantly with discrimination — it is not noble vairāgya but mere weakness.",
  '2.3': "क्लैब्यं मा स्म गमः — do not yield to unmanliness. Śaṅkara reads this as Krishna first treating Arjuna at the व्यावहारिक level: a kṣatriya's duty cannot be abandoned in moha; only after moha is named can the deeper teaching of the Self begin.",
  '2.4': "Arjuna asks how he can fight Bhīṣma and Droṇa, worthy of worship. Śaṅkara notes that Arjuna's argument has now retreated to ritual reverence, exposing how moha keeps shifting its grounds.",
  '2.5': "Arjuna prefers begging to killing teachers; the enjoyments would be blood-stained. Śaṅkara: the very word श्रेयः (better) is being misapplied — the true श्रेयस् is आत्मज्ञान, not avoidance of duty.",
  '2.6': "Arjuna does not know which is better — to win or to be defeated. Śaṅkara identifies this confusion as the practical condition that prepares for śaraṇa: only when the seeker admits incompetence in dharma does he become fit for instruction.",
  '2.7': "कार्पण्यदोषोपहतस्वभावः — Arjuna formally takes refuge as śiṣya. Śaṅkara marks this as the pivotal verse: the upodghāta-promised teaching can now begin, since the listener has the प्रवृत्ति of a disciple, not a debater.",
  '2.8': "Arjuna sees no remedy for the grief drying up his senses, even gaining a kingdom. Śaṅkara: ordinary remedies (kingdom, sense-pleasures) cannot dissolve शोक; only knowledge of the Self can, which is exactly what Krishna will provide.",
  '2.9': "Sañjaya reports that having said न योत्स्ये, Arjuna falls silent. Śaṅkara reads the silence as the precondition for true śravaṇa: when the disciple stops arguing, hearing becomes possible.",
  '2.10': "Krishna, smiling, addresses the dejected Arjuna between the two armies. Śaṅkara: the smile signals that the speaker is detached, knowing all this drama to occur within the empirical sphere; the teaching of the अद्वय आत्मा is about to commence.",
  '2.11': "अशोच्यान् अन्वशोचस्त्वम् — you grieve for those not to be grieved for, yet speak words of wisdom. Śaṅkara takes this as the true beginning of the Gītā śāstra: Arjuna's grief is misplaced because the body dies but the आत्मा does not, and the wise grieve for neither.",
  '2.12': "Never was there a time when I, you, and these kings did not exist. Śaṅkara: the verse establishes the eternality of the आत्मन्; the plurality of selves spoken of is upādhi-based, not ontological — at the पारमार्थिक level there is one Self.",
  '2.13': "As childhood, youth, age come to the embodied, so does another body — the wise are not deluded. Śaṅkara reads देहान्तरप्राप्ति as continuous identity of the Self through bodies, with the qualification that this is from the empirical (अविद्या-based) standpoint; the truly liberated has no body to acquire.",
  '2.14': "Sense contacts give heat, cold, pleasure, pain — they come and go; endure them, Bhārata. Śaṅkara: these are मात्रास्पर्शाः, only mātrā (limited modes); तितिक्षा is enjoined as preparation for steady knowledge, since pleasure-pain are not properties of the Self.",
  '2.15': "He whom these do not afflict, the wise, equal in pleasure and pain — he is fit for amṛtatva. Śaṅkara identifies this person as the आत्मज्ञान-aspirant; अमृतत्व is not heaven but mokṣa, the cessation of साम्सारिक identification.",
  '2.16': "नासतो विद्यते भावो — the unreal has no being, the real has no non-being. Śaṅkara takes this as the cardinal Advaita verse: सत् is the आत्मा (unchanging), असत् is the body and modifications (perishing); the seers (तत्त्वदर्शिनः) have ascertained their boundary.",
  '2.17': "That by which all this is pervaded is indestructible; no one can destroy the imperishable. Śaṅkara: the Self pervades the body without being affected; अविनाशि is its very nature, and no causal agent can alter it.",
  '2.18': "Bodies are perishable, the embodied is eternal, indestructible, immeasurable; therefore fight. Śaṅkara: from the truth of the Self comes the conclusion युध्यस्व — not because killing is good, but because the Self neither kills nor is killed; स्वधर्म proceeds without producing bondage.",
  '2.19': "He who thinks the Self kills or is killed — neither knows. Śaṅkara takes this as the negation of agency in the Self; killing is a transaction within prakṛti, never of the आत्मन्.",
  '2.20': "न जायते म्रियते वा कदाचित् — never born, never dies. Śaṅkara reads this verse as defining the Self by negation of all six भाव-विकार (becoming, being, growing, transforming, decaying, perishing); the Self is नित्य-शुद्ध-बुद्ध-मुक्त-स्वभाव.",
  '2.21': "He who knows the Self as indestructible, eternal, unborn, undecaying — how does such a one slay or cause to slay? Śaṅkara: knowledge of the निष्क्रियात्मा removes both agency and instigation; this verse is one of his strongest texts for ज्ञान-निष्ठा and the impossibility of combining ज्ञान with karma at the highest level.",
  '2.22': "As one casts off worn clothes and takes new ones, so the embodied takes new bodies. Śaṅkara: this is given in the व्यावहारिक register for those still under aviḍyā, to console; from the पारमार्थिक standpoint, the Self does not actually transmigrate.",
  '2.23': "Weapons cannot cut, fire cannot burn, water cannot wet, wind cannot dry it. Śaṅkara: the Self stands outside the four elements that destroy bodies; it is the substrate, not a member, of the elemental world.",
  '2.24': "Uncuttable, unburnable, unwettable, undriable; eternal, all-pervading, stable, immovable, ancient. Śaṅkara takes सर्वगतः as भगवान्'s own witness to the Self being like ākāśa — without limits, without parts.",
  '2.25': "Unmanifest, unthinkable, unchangeable — knowing thus, you should not grieve. Śaṅkara: avyakta here means not graspable by the senses; अविकार्य denies all transformation, ruling out parinama doctrines that would make the Self truly become something else.",
  '2.26': "Even if you think the Self is constantly born and constantly dies, you should not grieve. Śaṅkara reads this as a concession to the materialist: even on a non-Advaita view, grief over the inevitable is irrational.",
  '2.27': "For the born, death is certain; for the dead, birth — therefore you should not grieve over the unavoidable. Śaṅkara: a secondary argument; the primary is the Self's eternality, but even on lokāyata premises grief is unwarranted.",
  '2.28': "Beings are unmanifest before, manifest in the middle, unmanifest at end — what cause for lament? Śaṅkara reads this as a demonstration that the gross body is mostly avyakta even on the empirical view, so its temporary manifestation is no ground for attachment.",
  '2.29': "Some see the Self as a wonder, some speak of it as a wonder, some hear it as a wonder; even hearing, none truly know it. Śaṅkara takes आश्चर्य to mean that the Self is utterly other than anything in saṃsāra and so genuine knowledge is rare; mere śravaṇa is not yet realisation.",
  '2.30': "The dweller in every body is ever indestructible — therefore you should not grieve for any beings. Śaṅkara: the conclusion of the आत्मा-section; the Gītā now turns to स्वधर्म reasoning for the non-realised.",
  '2.31': "Considering also one's own dharma, you should not waver — for a kṣatriya there is nothing better than righteous war. Śaṅkara explicitly notes that this argument is for the still-embodied, not-yet-realised — स्वधर्म holds at the व्यावहारिक level, while ज्ञान-निष्ठा is for the few qualified.",
  '2.32': "Such a war, freely come, opens the gate of heaven — fortunate kṣatriyas get it. Śaṅkara: the verse uses heaven-language; for him this is artha-vāda showing that even at the karma level, refusing duty is shameful, not virtuous.",
  '2.33': "If you do not fight this dharmic battle, you abandon your dharma and fame and incur sin. Śaṅkara: the absence of dharma-action is itself a doer of evil; inaction is not neutrality.",
  '2.34': "People will ever speak of your disgrace; for the honoured, dishonour is worse than death. Śaṅkara: a worldly argument; included to demolish Arjuna's pretence of vairāgya.",
  '2.35': "The great warriors will think you withdrew from fear. Śaṅkara: the same artha-vāda continues — Arjuna's renunciation will not be read as renunciation by anyone competent.",
  '2.36': "Enemies will say things unfit to be heard about your prowess — what could be more painful? Śaṅkara: another consequentialist argument calibrated to Arjuna's still-warrior identity.",
  '2.37': "Slain, you reach heaven; victorious, you enjoy earth — therefore rise, son of Kuntī, resolved to fight. Śaṅkara: the win-win logic of स्वधर्म; either outcome is good, so the action is unconditionally indicated.",
  '2.38': "Treating pleasure and pain, gain and loss, victory and defeat as equal, gird yourself for battle — thus you incur no sin. Śaṅkara reads this as the bridge: समत्व here introduces the कर्मयोग attitude that will be developed from 2.39 onward.",
  '2.39': "This understanding has been told to you in sāṅkhya; now hear it in yoga — endowed with which you will cast off the bondage of karma. Śaṅkara identifies सांख्य here with ज्ञान-निष्ठा (the realised viewpoint of 2.11–30) and योग with कर्मयोग (the means for the non-realised); the two paths begin from the same truth.",
  '2.40': "In this (yoga), no effort is wasted, no ill effect; even a little of this dharma protects from great fear. Śaṅkara: कर्मयोग is पुरुषार्थ-effective from the very first step, unlike ritual karma which needs full completion.",
  '2.41': "Here, the resolute intellect is single; the irresolute have many-branched intellects. Śaṅkara: व्यवसायात्मिका बुद्धि is the focused intellect of the कर्मयोगी committed to liberation; बहुशाखाः बुद्धयः belong to those who pursue scattered ritual ends.",
  '2.42': "The undiscerning, devoted to flowery Vedic words, say there is nothing else. Śaṅkara reads this as a sharp critique not of the Vedas but of those who absolutise their कर्मकाण्ड portion and ignore the आत्म-knowledge portion (jñāna-kāṇḍa).",
  '2.43': "Those desiring heaven, full of desire, prescribe many specialised rituals for enjoyment and rebirth. Śaṅkara: the verse names exactly those who reduce the Veda to a means of svarga, missing its mokṣa-purport entirely.",
  '2.44': "Attached to enjoyment and power, with stolen minds, no resolute intellect arises in samādhi. Śaṅkara: kāma and adhikāra are the two great obstructors of the buddhi-yoga taught here.",
  '2.45': "The Vedas deal with the three guṇas; be free of the three guṇas, free of dualities, ever in sattva, free of acquisition and protection, possessed of the Self. Śaṅkara: निस्त्रैगुण्य = transcending even sattva; the goal is आत्मवान्, established in the Self, beyond the threefold gunamaya world.",
  '2.46': "As much use as a small water-tank in a place flooded everywhere, so much use are all the Vedas to a knower of brahman. Śaṅkara: a key verse — for the brahma-jñānī, the karmakāṇḍa loses purpose, since its results are subsumed in the highest result already attained.",
  '2.47': "कर्मण्येवाधिकारस्ते — your right is to action alone, never to the fruits. Śaṅkara takes this as the foundational karma-yoga rule for the unrealised: act from duty, abandon attachment to phala, but do not turn this into a license for inaction (मा ते सङ्गोऽस्त्वकर्मणि).",
  '2.48': "योगस्थः कुरु कर्माणि — established in yoga, do actions, casting off attachment, even-minded in success and failure; samatva is yoga. Śaṅkara: this is his classical definition of कर्मयोग — सिद्ध्यसिद्ध्योः समत्वम् — the equanimity that purifies the mind for ज्ञान.",
  '2.49': "Action with desire is far inferior to buddhi-yoga; take refuge in buddhi — pitiable are those motivated by fruit. Śaṅkara: कर्मयोग is superior precisely because it leads to mind-purification and thence to ज्ञान, while phala-driven action only reinforces saṃsāra.",
  '2.50': "The buddhi-yogī sheds both good and evil deeds here itself; therefore commit to yoga — yoga is skill in actions. Śaṅkara reads योगः कर्मसु कौशलम् as the art of doing karma without binding-residue, by the equanimity of buddhi-yoga.",
  '2.51': "The wise, of buddhi-yoga, having abandoned phala, freed of birth-bondage, reach the place beyond all ill (अनामयं पदम्). Śaṅkara: the destination is not heaven but mokṣa — the स्थान free of all worldly suffering.",
  '2.52': "When your buddhi crosses the thicket of delusion, you will reach indifference to what has been heard and what is yet to be heard. Śaṅkara: as discrimination matures, even śruti-prescriptions of karma become uninteresting because their phala has lost its grip.",
  '2.53': "When your buddhi, perplexed by śruti, stands fixed, motionless in samādhi, then you will attain yoga. Śaṅkara: समाधौ अचला — fixed in the Self; this is the यो का concluding lakṣaṇa of the buddhi-yogī, very close to the स्थितप्रज्ञ which the next section will define.",
  '2.54': "Arjuna asks: what are the marks of the स्थितप्रज्ञ — how does he speak, sit, walk? Śaṅkara reads the question as the disciple asking for the lakṣaṇas of the realised one (ज्ञानिन्), since 2.55ff is the first formal portrait of the ज्ञानी in the Gītā.",
  '2.55': "When one abandons all desires of the mind, content in the Self by the Self alone — then he is called स्थितप्रज्ञ. Śaṅkara: the लक्षण is आत्मन्येवात्मना तुष्टः — the contented Self resting in itself; this is the realised, not merely the practising, yogī.",
  '2.56': "Unagitated by sorrow, unattached to pleasure, free of attachment, fear, and anger — such a sage is स्थितधीः. Śaṅkara: here the marks are negative — absence of vītarāga, fear, and anger — characteristic of one who has dissolved अहंकार.",
  '2.57': "Without affection anywhere, neither rejoicing in good nor hating ill — his prajñā is established. Śaṅkara: the absence of रागद्वेष is structural, not behavioural mimicry; it follows from realisation, not from suppression.",
  '2.58': "When he withdraws senses from objects as a tortoise its limbs — his prajñā is established. Śaṅkara reads the कूर्मसिमिले as describing the realised one's spontaneous indrayanigraha, not a deliberate practice — natural withdrawal once Self-knowledge is firm.",
  '2.59': "Objects turn back from the abstaining embodied, but the rasa (taste/longing) remains; for one who has seen the Supreme, even rasa turns back. Śaṅkara takes this as proof that mere external control is incomplete — only परं दृष्ट्वा (seeing the Highest) eradicates the inward longing.",
  '2.60': "The turbulent senses forcibly carry away even the mind of a striving wise person. Śaṅkara: even sādhakas are warned; this verse is meant for the as-yet-unrealised yogī, not for the established ज्ञानी.",
  '2.61': "Restraining all those, let one sit in yoga, intent on me; for he whose senses are subdued, his prajñā is established. Śaṅkara reads मत्परः as devotion to the supreme Self (Īśvara as one's own Self), the inner orientation of the yogī.",
  '2.62': "Brooding on objects produces attachment; from attachment, desire; from frustrated desire, anger. Śaṅkara: the genealogy of bondage; abhidhyāyataḥ is the fatal first step that the realised has cut off.",
  '2.63': "From anger, delusion; from delusion, memory-loss; from memory-loss, ruin of buddhi; from ruin of buddhi, the man perishes. Śaṅkara: the chain ends in बुद्धिनाश — the destruction of discriminative wisdom — which is functional saṃsāric death.",
  '2.64': "But moving among objects with senses freed of rāga-dveṣa, self-controlled, he attains serenity. Śaṅkara: prasāda is चित्त-prasāda, the inner clarity that is the immediate seedbed of ज्ञान.",
  '2.65': "In serenity, all sorrows are destroyed; in the serene-minded, intellect quickly stabilises. Śaṅkara takes बुद्धिः पर्यवतिष्ठते as the steadying of the intellect in आत्म-jñāna — the precondition becomes the condition.",
  '2.66': "Without yoga there is no buddhi, no contemplation; without contemplation no peace, and without peace, no joy. Śaṅkara: ayuktasya — the unyogic mind — has no chance at śānti or sukha; the Gītā's order is yoga → buddhi → bhāvanā → śānti → sukha.",
  '2.67': "As the wind carries off a boat on the waters, so even one wandering sense seizes the prajñā. Śaṅkara: a single ungoverned sense suffices to ruin the mind, hence the necessity of comprehensive indriya-saṃyama.",
  '2.68': "Therefore, he whose senses are wholly withdrawn from objects — his prajñā is established. Śaṅkara: the conclusion of the indriya-discussion; उपसंहार verse defining the स्थितप्रज्ञ once more.",
  '2.69': "What is night for all beings is wakefulness for the संयमी; what is wakefulness for beings is night for the seeing sage. Śaṅkara reads this as the inversion of values: the world's day (sense-pleasure) is the sage's night, and the sage's day (आत्म-jñāna) is the world's night.",
  '2.70': "As waters enter the ocean which remains unmoved, so desires enter the wise without disturbing — he attains śānti, not the desire-driven. Śaṅkara: the simile is precise — desires enter (one cannot prevent contact) but produce no agitation in the realised; this is स्थितप्रज्ञ-fulfilment.",
  '2.71': "He who acts having abandoned all desires, free of longing, ego-less, possession-less — he attains śānti. Śaṅkara takes निर्ममः निरहंकारः as the explicit denial of the two forms of mis-identification (mine-ness and I-ness); their absence is mokṣa.",
  '2.72': "This is the brāhmī sthiti; attaining it, none is deluded; abiding in it even at the end, one attains brahma-nirvāṇa. Śaṅkara: the chapter closes with the highest teaching — ब्राह्मीस्थिति is not a state to be reached after death but right knowledge whose stability culminates in nirvāṇa, the cessation of saṃsāra in brahman.",

  // ===================== Chapter 3 (43 verses) =====================
  '3.1': "Arjuna asks: if buddhi is superior to karma, why this terrible action? Śaṅkara takes this question as evidence that two distinct paths have been taught — ज्ञान-निष्ठा and कर्म-निष्ठा — and the disciple is now rightly perplexed about which to follow; the chapter answers the eligibility question.",
  '3.2': "Your mixed words confuse me — tell me one thing definitely, by which I may attain the highest good. Śaṅkara: the question pre-supposes that the two niṣṭhās cannot be combined for one person; the bhāṣya famously defends this distinction throughout chapter 3.",
  '3.3': "Krishna replies: in this world, two niṣṭhās have been declared by me — ज्ञानयोग for the सांख्ययोगी, कर्मयोग for the योगी. Śaṅkara takes this as the cardinal text supporting the doctrine that ज्ञान-निष्ठा belongs to the renunciate sannyāsin and कर्म-निष्ठा to the householder; the two are sequential, not simultaneous, for the same person.",
  '3.4': "Not by abstaining from action does one attain naiṣkarmya; not by mere renunciation does one reach perfection. Śaṅkara: external karma-tyāga without inner purity yields nothing; अनारंभात् alone is not the path — purification must precede true sannyāsa.",
  '3.5': "No one can remain even a moment without acting; everyone is forced to act by the guṇas of prakṛti. Śaṅkara: this is empirically true for the अज्ञानी; the ज्ञानी, having identified with the निष्क्रियात्मा, is no longer the agent — but for the embodied unrealised, action is unavoidable.",
  '3.6': "He who restrains action-organs but mentally dwells on objects — that deluded one is called a hypocrite. Śaṅkara: मिथ्याचारः; mere external withdrawal with internal indulgence is worse than honest action.",
  '3.7': "But he who controls the senses by the mind and engages the action-organs in karmayoga, unattached — he is superior. Śaṅkara: कर्मयोग with internal mastery is far above feigned renunciation; this verse legitimises action as a valid path.",
  '3.8': "Do your prescribed action; action is better than inaction; even bodily maintenance cannot proceed without action. Śaṅkara: नियतं कर्म = वर्ण-आश्रम-prescribed; even prāṇa-yātrā depends on karma, so total inaction is impossible for the embodied.",
  '3.9': "Action other than for yajña binds the world; therefore, free of attachment, perform action for the sake of yajña. Śaṅkara reads यज्ञ here broadly as Īśvara-arpana — work offered to the Lord — which detaches the act from binding fruit.",
  '3.10': "Prajāpati created beings together with yajña, saying: by this you shall propagate, and this will be your wish-yielding cow. Śaṅkara: yajña is the cosmic order built into creation; karma-yoga aligns the agent with that order.",
  '3.11': "By this nourish the gods and they will nourish you; by mutual nourishment, attain the highest good. Śaṅkara: he reads परस्परं भावयन्तः at both the literal vedic-yajña level and metaphorically as the inter-dependence of duties.",
  '3.12': "The gods, satisfied with yajña, give desired enjoyments; he who enjoys their gifts without offering back is a thief. Śaṅkara: स्तेन एव — strong word; karma-yoga is also a debt-balancing discipline that extracts the seeker from theft-status.",
  '3.13': "The good who eat the leftovers of yajña are freed of all sins; the wicked who cook only for themselves eat sin. Śaṅkara: यज्ञशिष्टाशिनः — even ordinary eating becomes purifying when subordinated to yajña-attitude.",
  '3.14': "Beings come from food, food from rain, rain from yajña, yajña from karma. Śaṅkara reads this cycle as showing the integration of the empirical world; karma-yoga participates in maintaining it without binding the agent.",
  '3.15': "Karma comes from brahman (the Veda), brahman from akṣara — therefore the all-pervading brahman is ever fixed in yajña. Śaṅkara takes brahman here as Veda; the chain grounds karma in śruti, but the highest brahman remains beyond it.",
  '3.16': "He who does not turn this revolving wheel here on earth lives in vain, indulging the senses. Śaṅkara: not following the cosmic karma-cycle while still embodied is illegitimate; only the realised escape it by transcending agency itself.",
  '3.17': "But for one rejoicing in the Self, content in the Self, satisfied in the Self — for him there is nothing yet to be done. Śaṅkara: this is his decisive verse for जीवन्मुक्त — the आत्मरतिः has no further duty; chapter 3 explicitly admits that ज्ञान-निष्ठा is exempt from karma.",
  '3.18': "He has no purpose served by action done or undone, no dependence on any being for any purpose. Śaṅkara: a strong text against combining ज्ञान with karma — the ज्ञानिन्'s कृतकृत्यता is total; he has no surplus duty.",
  '3.19': "Therefore, ever unattached, perform the action that ought to be done; the unattached agent attains the Supreme. Śaṅkara: addressed to the still-embodied non-realised — कर्मयोग leads to the Supreme via citta-śuddhi and ज्ञान.",
  '3.20': "By karma alone, Janaka and others reached perfection; even for the welfare of the world, you should act. Śaṅkara reads जनकादयः as those who attained ज्ञान through prior karma-yoga; लोकसङ्ग्रह is the secondary motive that survives in the leader-figure for the sake of others.",
  '3.21': "Whatever a great person does, others do; whatever standard he sets, the world follows. Śaṅkara: the duty of leadership is not optional for one in a public role; even the realised, while bodied, may continue to act for लोकसङ्ग्रह.",
  '3.22': "I have nothing to attain, nothing unattained, yet I act. Śaṅkara: Krishna as Īśvara has no personal stake; the example shows that purposeless action without personal want is possible — and that is exactly what कर्मयोग asks.",
  '3.23': "If I did not act tirelessly, all people would follow my example. Śaṅkara: the cosmological consequence of divine inaction would be world-collapse; the verse anchors the loka-saṅgraha argument in Īśvara's own conduct.",
  '3.24': "If I did not work, these worlds would perish; I would be the cause of varṇa-saṅkara and destroy these creatures. Śaṅkara: even at the divine level, action sustains the order; inaction is not an option that produces good.",
  '3.25': "The unwise act with attachment; the wise should act without attachment, desiring loka-saṅgraha. Śaṅkara: the wise's action is structurally the same as the ignorant's, but its psychology and result differ entirely — that is the whole point of कर्मयोग.",
  '3.26': "Let the wise not unsettle the buddhi of the ignorant attached to action; engaged himself, he should make them engage. Śaṅkara: the ज्ञानिन् should not destabilise the karma-faith of those still requiring it; his own action becomes a teaching device.",
  '3.27': "All actions are done by the guṇas of prakṛti; the ego-deluded thinks 'I am the doer'. Śaṅkara reads this as the cardinal anti-agency verse: कर्तृत्व is in prakṛti, not in the आत्मन्; the अहंकार-vimūḍha mistake is exactly the bondage to be removed.",
  '3.28': "He who knows the truth of guṇa and karma — that guṇas operate on guṇas — does not attach. Śaṅkara: the realised sees only guṇa-vyāpāra and stands apart as the witness; this is liberation in the very midst of activity.",
  '3.29': "Those deluded by the guṇas of prakṛti remain attached; the all-knower should not unsettle them. Śaṅkara: even Krishna will not preach naiṣkarmya prematurely to the unfit — the chapter strongly upholds adhikāri-bheda.",
  '3.30': "Casting all actions on me, with adhyātma-cetas, free of desire, of mineness, of fever — fight! Śaṅkara: मयि सर्वाणि कर्माणि सन्न्यस्य is the karma-yoga interim formula — surrender to Īśvara, who is one's own Self for the realised but the supreme Lord for the practising.",
  '3.31': "Those who, with faith and without complaint, follow this teaching of mine are also freed from karma. Śaṅkara: even श्रद्धावन्तः, without realisation yet, gain karma-mukti by faithfully following karma-yoga.",
  '3.32': "Those who, complaining, do not follow it — know them as ruined of all knowledge, deluded, lost. Śaṅkara: the rejection of the teaching itself is the obstacle; without faith, even śravaṇa fails.",
  '3.33': "Even the wise act according to their own prakṛti; beings follow prakṛti — what will repression accomplish? Śaṅkara: नताभिशंकया — repression alone, without ज्ञान, does not work; the structural transformation requires knowledge, not coercion.",
  '3.34': "Sense-attachment and aversion are seated in their objects; let no one fall under their power — they are the enemies. Śaṅkara: रागद्वेष are the great paripanthins; their conquest is the whole work of sādhana.",
  '3.35': "Better one's own dharma poorly performed than another's well done; better death in own dharma — paradharma is fearful. Śaṅkara: स्वधर्म = प्रकृति-aligned duty; the verse rejects external switching of role at the व्यावहारिक level, while obviously not contradicting the ज्ञानिन्'s transcendence of all roles.",
  '3.36': "Arjuna asks: by what is one impelled to sin even unwillingly, as if forced? Śaṅkara: the disciple's question opens space for the diagnosis of kāma — the chapter's climactic enemy.",
  '3.37': "Krishna names it: this is kāma, this is krodha, born of rajas — the great devourer, the great sinner; know it as the enemy here. Śaṅkara: rajoguṇa-samudbhavaḥ — desire and anger are not properties of the Self but products of rajas; their identification with us is misidentification.",
  '3.38': "As fire is covered by smoke, mirror by dust, embryo by membrane — so is this (knowledge) covered by it (kāma). Śaṅkara: tri-fold simile; kāma occludes ज्ञान just as smoke occludes flame — removable, not intrinsic to the Self.",
  '3.39': "Knowledge is covered by this constant enemy of the wise — by kāma in the form of an insatiable fire. Śaṅkara: दुष्पूरेण आनलेन — the metaphor of insatiable fire underscores kāma's structural lack of fulfilment.",
  '3.40': "Senses, mind, and intellect are said to be its abode; from these it deludes the embodied, covering knowledge. Śaṅkara identifies the seat of kāma in the inner instruments — its proper conquest must be inward, not merely external.",
  '3.41': "Therefore, restraining the senses first, slay this sinner, the destroyer of knowledge and discrimination. Śaṅkara: the chronological order — first sense-control, then ज्ञान-vijñāna-nāśakam आहत्त — is intentional pedagogy.",
  '3.42': "Senses are higher than the body, mind higher than senses, intellect higher than mind — and beyond intellect is He (the Self). Śaṅkara takes the gradation as the practising path: progressively withdraw identification toward the आत्मन्, which alone is param.",
  '3.43': "Knowing thus what is beyond intellect, steadying the self by the Self, slay this hard-to-conquer enemy in the form of kāma. Śaṅkara: आत्मना आत्मानम् संस्तभ्य — by the higher Self steady the lower; only when ज्ञान has revealed the para is kāma truly conquerable. The chapter closes by linking कर्मयोग to its eventual fruit, ज्ञान.",

  // ===================== Chapter 4 (42 verses) =====================
  '4.1': "Krishna says: this imperishable yoga I told to Vivasvān, he to Manu, Manu to Ikṣvāku. Śaṅkara reads the disclosure of the paramparā as showing that yoga (here the karma-yoga that culminates in ज्ञान) is the very ancient royal path, not a novelty; the lineage establishes its authority and its kṣatriya transmission.",
  '4.2': "The royal sages knew it through tradition; in long time the yoga was lost. Śaṅkara: कालेन योगो नष्टः — in the absence of strong adhikāris, the line breaks; the verse motivates Krishna's restatement.",
  '4.3': "That same ancient yoga I tell you today, for you are my devotee and friend — this is the highest secret. Śaṅkara: भक्तः and सखा signify the eligibility — surrender plus intimate trust opens the rahasya.",
  '4.4': "Arjuna asks: how can your birth, later, be earlier than Vivasvān's? Śaṅkara: a natural objection on the व्यावहारिक level which sets up the next verse's revelation of avatāra-tattva.",
  '4.5': "Many births of mine and yours have passed; I know them all, you do not. Śaṅkara: omniscience belongs to the avatāra by māyā-śakti; ordinary jīvas, by aviḍyā, do not recall their births — the asymmetry is doctrinal, not just psychological.",
  '4.6': "Though unborn and imperishable, lord of beings, by my own māyā I take birth, holding my own prakṛti. Śaṅkara: आत्ममायया — Krishna's birth is not real birth in the bondage sense; māyā here is the divine śakti that allows the formless to appear as form without ontological loss.",
  '4.7': "Whenever dharma declines and adharma rises, I create myself. Śaṅkara: सृजाम्यहम् आत्मानम् — apparent self-creation; from the highest standpoint nothing actually new comes into being, but for the world's sake the divine appears.",
  '4.8': "For protection of the good, destruction of the wicked, establishment of dharma — I take birth age after age. Śaṅkara: the avatāra-prayojana is dharma-saṃsthāpana; this is repeated, structural, and not personal.",
  '4.9': "He who knows my divine birth and works thus, on leaving the body, does not come to rebirth — he comes to me. Śaṅkara reads the knowledge of the avatāra-tattva as itself liberating, since it is correlative to the knowledge that the Self is not a born/dying entity.",
  '4.10': "Free of attachment, fear, anger, full of me, taking refuge in me, purified by the tapas of knowledge — many have come to my state. Śaṅkara: ज्ञानतपसा पूताः — knowledge as the highest tapas; अनेके reaches my-state — not different selves arriving at different places, but unification with the same para.",
  '4.11': "As they approach me, so I receive them; in every way men follow my path. Śaṅkara: यथा यथा — proportional response; Īśvara is the same to all but reflects according to the seeker's stance, like a mirror.",
  '4.12': "Those desiring siddhi worship the gods here; in this human world karma's fruit comes quickly. Śaṅkara: a concession to lower adhikāris; the quick fruit is fine for those of small aim, but it is not mokṣa.",
  '4.13': "The four-fold varṇa was created by me according to guṇa and karma; though its agent, know me as non-agent and imperishable. Śaṅkara: chaturvarṇya-sṛṣṭi is by guṇa-karma classification; yet कर्तारमपि अकर्तारम् — Īśvara is the apparent doer but truly non-doer, paralleling the Self.",
  '4.14': "Actions do not stain me, nor do I have any longing for their fruits; he who knows me thus is not bound by actions. Śaṅkara: the ज्ञानी who replicates this stance — agency without phala-spṛhā — is unbound, exactly as Īśvara is.",
  '4.15': "Knowing this, the ancients sought liberation through action; therefore do action as the ancients did. Śaṅkara: even the ancient mumukṣus did karma-yoga; the verse forestalls the objection 'how can a liberation-seeker act?'",
  '4.16': "Even the wise are confused about action and inaction; I will tell you that knowing which you will be free from evil. Śaṅkara: the kim-karma kim-akarma question is genuinely subtle and Śaṅkara devotes considerable bhāṣya to it; the answer reframes both terms by reference to agency, not movement.",
  '4.17': "The nature of action, of forbidden action, and of inaction must be known — the way of action is hard to grasp. Śaṅkara: gahana — because the same external movement may be karma, vikarma, or akarma depending on inner state.",
  '4.18': "He who sees inaction in action and action in inaction is wise among men, a yogī, a doer of all actions. Śaṅkara takes this as one of his most cited verses for ज्ञान-निष्ठा: the realised sees that the Self never acts even when the body acts (inaction-in-action), and that mere bodily inactivity is not akarma if mental agency persists.",
  '4.19': "He whose every undertaking is free of desire and resolve, whose karma is burned by the fire of knowledge — the wise call him paṇḍita. Śaṅkara: ज्ञानाग्नि-दग्ध-कर्माणम् — the technical doctrine that ज्ञान burns saṃcita-karma; only the realised reaches this status.",
  '4.20': "Abandoning attachment to fruit, ever satisfied, depending on nothing — though engaged in action, he does nothing. Śaṅkara: not metaphor but doctrine — the realised is functionally a non-actor while the body continues karma; this anchors ज्ञान-निष्ठा's compatibility with embodied life.",
  '4.21': "Without expectation, with mind and self restrained, abandoning all possessions, performing only bodily action, he incurs no fault. Śaṅkara: शारीरं केवलं कर्म — actions necessary for body-maintenance only; this is the realised's external profile.",
  '4.22': "Content with what comes by chance, beyond the dualities, free of envy, balanced in success and failure — though acting, he is not bound. Śaṅkara: the यदृच्छा-लाभ-सन्तुष्टः portrait describes the जीवन्मुक्त, who continues life in body without fresh karma-binding.",
  '4.23': "For the unattached, liberated, of mind established in knowledge, performing action as yajña — his entire karma dissolves. Śaṅkara: यज्ञायाचरतः कर्म — yajña-attitude functions as the solvent for karma's binding power.",
  '4.24': "Brahman the offering, brahman the oblation, by brahman offered into the brahman-fire — by brahman-action focus, brahman alone is to be reached. Śaṅkara reads this as the perfectly Advaitic rendering of yajña: when the agent sees only brahman in every component, the action ceases to be karma at all and becomes ज्ञान-yajña.",
  '4.25': "Some yogīs offer yajña to gods; others offer the self in the brahman-fire. Śaṅkara distinguishes the lower (देवयज्ञ) from the higher (आत्म-yajña-as-brahman); the latter is for the ज्ञान-aspirant.",
  '4.26': "Some offer hearing and senses in the fires of restraint; others offer sound and objects in the senses. Śaṅkara: yajña-spectrum extends to ascetic disciplines (इन्द्रिय-संयम-yajña) and even to the deliberate engagement of senses in objects with awareness.",
  '4.27': "Some offer the activities of senses and prāṇas in the fire of self-restraining yoga, kindled by knowledge. Śaṅkara: the inward yajña of prāṇa and indriya is the proximate path to ज्ञान.",
  '4.28': "Some perform yajña of wealth, of tapas, of yoga, of svādhyāya, of knowledge — strict ascetics. Śaṅkara: enumeration of legitimate yajñas; among these, ज्ञान-yajña will be declared supreme.",
  '4.29': "Some offer prāṇa in apāna and apāna in prāṇa, regulating breath, devoted to prāṇāyāma. Śaṅkara: the breath-yajña of prāṇāyāma is included for completeness but not elevated above ज्ञान-yajña.",
  '4.30': "Some, restraining food, offer prāṇas in prāṇas; all these, knowing yajña, have their sins destroyed by yajña. Śaṅkara: even niyat-āhāra is yajña; the common feature is purification of mind toward ज्ञान.",
  '4.31': "Yajña-eaters of nectar-remnants reach eternal brahman; not even this world is for the non-yajña-er. Śaṅkara: यज्ञशिष्टामृतभुजः — those who live on yajña-leftovers (literal and figurative) attain sanātana brahman; without yajña, even loka is denied — let alone para-loka.",
  '4.32': "Many such yajñas are spread before the face of brahman; know them all as karma-born; thus knowing, you will be liberated. Śaṅkara: कर्मजान् विद्धि तान् — all yajñas are karma-arising and therefore preparatory; ज्ञान alone is the actual moksha-cause.",
  '4.33': "Better than yajña of wealth is yajña of knowledge; all karmas in their entirety culminate in knowledge. Śaṅkara takes ज्ञानयज्ञ here as the rite of jñāna itself; सर्वं कर्माखिलं ज्ञाने परिसमाप्यते is one of his strongest texts for ज्ञान-supremacy.",
  '4.34': "Know it by prostration, questioning, service — the wise who have seen the truth will instruct you in knowledge. Śaṅkara: the upadeśa-method — humble approach to a tattva-darśin guru; ज्ञान is taught, not invented.",
  '4.35': "Knowing which you will not fall into delusion again; by which you will see all beings in the Self and in me. Śaṅkara: सर्वभूतानि आत्मनि — the central Advaitic seeing; the sage no longer perceives jīva-multiplicity as ultimate.",
  '4.36': "Even the worst of sinners crosses all evil by the boat of knowledge. Śaṅkara: ज्ञान-plava — knowledge is the boat across saṃsāra-ocean; even prior pāpa is dissolved.",
  '4.37': "As fire reduces firewood to ashes, so the fire of knowledge reduces all karmas to ashes. Śaṅkara cites this for the doctrine that ज्ञान destroys saṃcita karma without exception; only prārabdha continues by its own momentum.",
  '4.38': "Nothing in this world purifies like knowledge; in time, the perfected yogī finds it within himself. Śaṅkara: यः परिपूर्णः — the prepared one finds ज्ञान within when the सायेव outer support culminates inwardly.",
  '4.39': "The faithful, devoted, sense-controlled gain knowledge; gaining it, he attains supreme peace at once. Śaṅkara: श्रद्धावान् लभते ज्ञानं is enlisted as the standard prerequisite-list — śraddhā, tatparatā, indriya-saṃyama.",
  '4.40': "The ignorant and the doubting perish; for the doubter there is neither this world nor the next nor happiness. Śaṅkara: संशयात्मा is uniquely ruined — even ignorance with faith may be ratable, but doubt destroys all yajña and all loka.",
  '4.41': "He whose karma is renounced by yoga, whose doubt is severed by knowledge, possessed of the Self — actions do not bind. Śaṅkara: this is his classic ज्ञान-sannyāsa figure: yoga first, then ज्ञान, results in ātmavān status where karma is not binding.",
  '4.42': "Therefore, with the sword of knowledge, sever this ignorance-born doubt in the heart; resort to yoga; arise, Bhārata. Śaṅkara: ज्ञान-असि — the sword image; doubt is heart-resident (हृत्स्थम्) and cut from the inside; योगम् आतिष्ठ — and meanwhile, do karma-yoga.",

  // ===================== Chapter 5 (29 verses) =====================
  '5.1': "Arjuna asks: you praise renunciation of action and yoga of action — say definitely which is better. Śaṅkara: the chapter clarifies the relationship between sannyāsa and karma-yoga; the question presupposes their distinctness, which Śaṅkara strongly upholds.",
  '5.2': "Both lead to highest good; but of the two, karma-yoga is superior to mere karma-renunciation. Śaṅkara: superior in the sense of being more universally accessible and more reliably purifying for the unfit; the realised's sannyāsa is still ultimately higher when he is qualified.",
  '5.3': "Know him as the eternal sannyāsin who neither hates nor desires; free of dvandvas, he is easily released. Śaṅkara: नित्यसन्न्यासी — the karma-yogī of clarified mind functions as a sannyāsī even while acting; this defends sannyāsa-via-karma-yoga.",
  '5.4': "Children, not paṇḍitas, declare sāṅkhya and yoga separate; one well-established in either gains the fruit of both. Śaṅkara: एकम् अप्यास्थितः — ekam refers to either path correctly pursued; yet his bhāṣya keeps the two niṣṭhās distinct in practice while accepting that their fruit converges.",
  '5.5': "The state attained by sāṅkhyas is also attained by yogīs; he who sees sāṅkhya and yoga as one truly sees. Śaṅkara: the convergence is at the level of the result (mokṣa), not at the level of method; the methods remain stratified by adhikāra.",
  '5.6': "Sannyāsa is hard to attain without yoga; the muni in yoga quickly reaches brahman. Śaṅkara reads this as definitive support for the order: karma-yoga first, then sannyāsa; trying to renounce karma without first achieving inner purity is futile.",
  '5.7': "The yogī of pure self, mind-conquered, sense-conquered, whose self is the Self of all beings — though acting, is not stained. Śaṅkara: सर्वभूतात्मभूतात्मा — the realised yogī sees only the one Self; this is the explicit Advaita description.",
  '5.8': "नैव किञ्चित्करोमीति — 'I do nothing at all' — the yukta sees thus while seeing, hearing, touching, eating, going. Śaṅkara: this is one of his most cited verses for निष्क्रियात्मा; the realised attributes all activity to indriya-vyāpāra and stands as the witness, not the doer.",
  '5.9': "Speaking, releasing, grasping, opening, closing eyes — knowing 'senses move among objects'. Śaṅkara: इन्द्रियाणि इन्द्रियार्थेषु वर्तन्ते — guṇa-on-guṇa, with the आत्मन् entirely separate; the witness-doctrine in operative form.",
  '5.10': "He who acts placing actions in brahman, abandoning attachment, is not stained — like a lotus leaf untouched by water. Śaṅkara: padmapatra-simile; brahmaṇi karmāṇi sannyasya = surrendering all action to the Lord/the Self, the technique of karma-yoga that prevents staining.",
  '5.11': "Yogīs perform action by body, mind, intellect, senses, abandoning attachment, for self-purification. Śaṅkara: आत्मशुद्धि is the explicit aim of karma-yoga — the verse names the chapter's pivot, that karma-yoga is purificatory, not finally salvific.",
  '5.12': "The yukta, abandoning fruit, attains lasting peace; the unyukta, attached to fruit by desire, is bound. Śaṅkara: नैष्ठिकीं शान्तिम् — the lasting peace beyond fluctuating success; karma-phala-tyāga is its very gateway.",
  '5.13': "Renouncing all actions by mind, the embodied dweller in the nine-gated city sits at ease, neither acting nor causing action. Śaṅkara: navadvāre pure — the nine-gated city is the body; the realised dwells in it without identifying with its actions; this is sannyāsa-via-knowledge.",
  '5.14': "The Lord (the Self in this body) creates neither agency nor actions nor connection with fruits — prakṛti acts by its own nature. Śaṅkara: न कर्तृत्वं... स्वभावस्तु प्रवर्तते — the cardinal anti-agency text; agency belongs to prakṛti's svabhāva, not to the आत्मन्.",
  '5.15': "The all-pervading does not take on anyone's sin or merit; knowledge is covered by ignorance — beings are deluded thereby. Śaṅkara: ज्ञानेन तु तदज्ञानम् — agency-attribution is an aviḍyā-effect; the real Self never inherits good or bad karma.",
  '5.16': "But for those whose ignorance is destroyed by knowledge, knowledge illumines That Supreme like the sun. Śaṅkara: आदित्यवत् — the brahman is self-luminous; ज्ञान only removes the cloud of ignorance, it does not produce a new object.",
  '5.17': "Whose buddhi, ātman, niṣṭhā, parāyaṇa is in That, with sins washed by knowledge, they reach the unreturning state. Śaṅkara: तत्परायणाः — wholly oriented to brahman; अपुनरावृत्ति is the technical mokṣa-marker.",
  '5.18': "Brahmin, cow, elephant, dog, dog-eater — the wise see them with equal vision. Śaṅkara: समदर्शिनः — based on perceiving the same आत्मन् in all; not ethical pluralism but ontological identity.",
  '5.19': "Those whose mind is fixed in equanimity have already conquered creation here — brahman is faultless and even, hence they abide in brahman. Śaṅkara: इहैव तैः जितः सर्गः — saṃsāra is conquered while embodied (jīvanmukti); ब्रह्म समम् — brahman is the perfect equanimity.",
  '5.20': "Not rejoicing in good, not loathing the disagreeable — of unwavering buddhi, undeluded brahma-knower, he abides in brahman. Śaṅkara: ब्रह्मविद् ब्रह्मणि स्थितः — knowledge and abidance are co-instantiated.",
  '5.21': "His self unattached to outer contacts finds joy in the Self; with self yoked to brahman through yoga, he reaches imperishable bliss. Śaṅkara: अक्षयं सुखम् — the bliss is not produced but uncovered when the false sources are renounced.",
  '5.22': "Pleasures from sense-contact are sources of pain, with beginning and end — the wise do not delight in them. Śaṅkara: दुःखयोनयः — sense-pleasure is structurally suffering's cause; this is one of his strongest viveka-statements.",
  '5.23': "He who, here itself before liberation, can withstand the surge of desire and anger — he is the yogī, he the happy man. Śaṅkara: इह एव — even before death; the prefix is decisive — mokṣa is for the living, not a future-life event.",
  '5.24': "He whose joy, delight, and light are within — that yogī, becoming brahman, attains brahma-nirvāṇa. Śaṅkara: अन्तःसुखः अन्तरारामः — the delight has migrated entirely inward; ब्रह्मभूतः marks identity, not approach.",
  '5.25': "Sages whose sins are destroyed, dualities cut, self-controlled, working for the welfare of all beings, attain brahma-nirvāṇa. Śaṅkara: सर्वभूतहिते रताः — the realised continue beneficial action without personal attachment, exactly as the avatāra does.",
  '5.26': "For those self-controlled ascetics, free of desire and anger, knowing the Self — brahma-nirvāṇa is on every side. Śaṅkara: अभितः वर्तते — nirvāṇa is not far away or future; it surrounds the realised here and now.",
  '5.27': "Shutting out external contacts, fixing the gaze between the brows, equalising prāṇa and apāna in the nostrils. Śaṅkara: this and the next verses are dhyāna-prescription for the practising yogī; the realised does not need them but the sādhaka does.",
  '5.28': "Restraining senses, mind, intellect, with desire-fear-anger gone, intent on liberation — that muni is ever liberated. Śaṅkara: सदा मुक्त एव — present-tense mukti, again refusing the post-mortem reading.",
  '5.29': "Knowing me as enjoyer of yajñas and tapas, great Lord of all, friend of all beings — he attains śānti. Śaṅkara reads suhṛdam sarva-bhūtānām as the supreme Lord's universal friendliness; recognition of this is the same as recognition of the Self that is in all, since at the highest level the two are non-different.",

  // ===================== Chapter 6 (47 verses) =====================
  '6.1': "He who does prescribed action without depending on fruit is the sannyāsī and the yogī, not he without fire and rite. Śaṅkara: कार्यं कर्म — action that ought to be done; अनाश्रितः कर्मफलम् — phala-tyāga is the marker; mere external abandonment of agnihotra is not sannyāsa, and Śaṅkara explicitly refuses such laxist readings.",
  '6.2': "What they call sannyāsa, know that as yoga; no one becomes a yogī without renouncing saṅkalpa. Śaṅkara: सङ्कल्प-त्याग is the inner core of both yoga and sannyāsa; the verse identifies the two at the level of content, while their pratyāsthāna can differ.",
  '6.3': "For the muni climbing toward yoga, action is the means; for one already on the summit, śama is the means. Śaṅkara: ārurukṣu vs. yogārūḍha — the sādhaka uses karma-yoga; the realised uses śama (cessation); the verse formalises the staging that the bhāṣya defends throughout.",
  '6.4': "When one is unattached to sense-objects and to actions, having renounced all saṅkalpas — then he is called यogārūḍha. Śaṅkara: निःसङ्कल्पता is the lakṣaṇa of the summit; the standard, again, is internal not external.",
  '6.5': "Let one raise the self by the Self, not lower the self; for the Self alone is friend of self and Self alone is enemy. Śaṅkara: आत्मा एव हि आत्मनः बन्धुः — the conditioned self is friend or foe to itself depending on viveka; no external agent does this work.",
  '6.6': "For one who has conquered the self, the Self is friend; for the unconquered, the Self acts as enemy. Śaṅkara: आत्मा हि आत्मनः शत्रुवत् — the same Self, depending on identification, is liberator or jailer.",
  '6.7': "For the self-conquered, ever serene one, Paramātmā is samāhita in cold-heat, joy-sorrow, honour-dishonour. Śaṅkara: समाहितः — collected, established; the dvandva-titikṣā is the practical sign of paramātmā-stiti.",
  '6.8': "Content with knowledge and discrimination, on the peak, sense-conquered, equal to clod-stone-gold — he is called yukta. Śaṅkara: सम-लोष्ट्र-अश्म-काञ्चनः — equality not of price but of subject-relation; gold, stone, and clod are equally not-self.",
  '6.9': "Equal-minded toward friend, foe, neutral, judge, hateful, kinsman, good, evil — he excels. Śaṅkara: समबुद्धिः — the perception of one Self in all renders these social distinctions ontologically thin.",
  '6.10': "The yogī should constantly yoke himself in solitude, alone, restrained, free of desires and possessions. Śaṅkara: रहसि एकाकी — solitude is needed for the practising yogī; not for the realised, who carries solitude within.",
  '6.11': "In a clean place, having set a firm seat — neither too high nor too low, of cloth, deer-skin, kuśa. Śaṅkara reads the prescription as the practical setup for dhyāna-yoga; not allegorised; the chapter does include actual dhyāna-vidhi.",
  '6.12': "There, focusing the mind on a single point, restraining mind and senses, sitting on the seat, let him practise yoga for self-purification. Śaṅkara: आत्मविशुद्धये — even dhyāna is for citta-śuddhi here; the chapter explicitly subordinates technique to inner cleansing.",
  '6.13': "Holding body, head, neck erect, motionless, gazing at nose-tip without looking around. Śaṅkara: posture is precise but instrumental; the goal is not posture but mind-collection.",
  '6.14': "Serene self, fearless, fixed in brahmacarya, mind controlled, intent on me — he should sit in yoga. Śaṅkara: मच्चित्तः — mat = paramātman, also the inmost Self; this is dhyāna-on-the-Self.",
  '6.15': "Constantly yoking the self thus, the yogī of restrained mind attains the peace culminating in nirvāṇa, abiding in me. Śaṅkara: मत्संस्थाम् — abiding in brahman; nirvāṇa-paramā śāntiḥ is again present-tense.",
  '6.16': "Yoga is not for the over-eater nor the wholly abstainer, nor the over-sleeper nor the perpetually awake. Śaṅkara: मात्रा (measure) governs all yogāṅgas; extremes destroy, the middle nourishes.",
  '6.17': "For one who is yukta in eating, yukta in moving, yukta in actions, yukta in sleep and waking — yoga becomes destroyer of sorrow. Śaṅkara: yukta — moderate; दुःखहा योगो भवति — the dhyāna's effect is the cessation of duḥkha at its very root, the false identification.",
  '6.18': "When the controlled mind rests in the Self alone, free of longing for any desire — then he is called yukta. Śaṅkara: आत्मन्येव अवतिष्ठते — rest in the Self by abandoning desires; this is samādhi-lakṣaṇa.",
  '6.19': "As a lamp in a windless place does not flicker — that simile is given for the controlled-mind yogī meditating on the Self. Śaṅkara: नीवात-दीप-simile; the yogic mind, like the lamp, is unmoved when external winds (sense-contacts) are excluded.",
  '6.20': "Where the mind ceases, restrained by yoga; where seeing the Self by the Self, one is content in the Self. Śaṅkara: आत्मना आत्मानम् पश्यन् — the threefold formula characteristic of Advaita; the Self knowing itself by itself, not via an external object.",
  '6.21': "He knows that infinite happiness graspable only by buddhi beyond the senses — established there, he does not depart from the truth. Śaṅkara: अतीन्द्रियं सुखम् — the bliss is not sense-bliss; the knower stands rooted in tattva permanently.",
  '6.22': "Gaining which one thinks no other gain greater — established there, he is not shaken by even great sorrow. Śaṅkara: गुरुणाऽपि दुःखेन — the great-sorrow test; the realised stands.",
  '6.23': "Let it be known as duḥkha-saṃyoga-viyoga — separation from union with sorrow — yoga; let it be practised with determination, undespondent. Śaṅkara: a definition of yoga as the disjunction from sorrow-conjunction; not a positive acquisition but a negation of the false attachment.",
  '6.24': "Abandoning saṅkalpa-born desires, restraining all senses by the mind. Śaṅkara: सङ्कल्पप्रभवान् कामान् — desires arise from imagination, not from objects; their cure is at the imagination-level.",
  '6.25': "Slowly, slowly, by buddhi held by determination, settling the mind on the Self, let him think nothing else. Śaṅkara: शनैः शनैः — gradualism is built into the practice; sudden suppression backfires.",
  '6.26': "Wherever the unstable, restless mind wanders, restraining it from there, let him bring it under the Self's control. Śaṅkara: यतो यतो निश्चरति — the technique handles the mind's spontaneous escapes; the practice is iterative.",
  '6.27': "To the yogī of pacified mind, of pacified rajas, brahma-bhūta, faultless — supreme bliss comes. Śaṅkara: ब्रह्मभूतम् — having become brahman, not merely contemplating it; this is the realisation-event.",
  '6.28': "Constantly yoking himself thus, sin-free, the yogī easily attains the limitless bliss of brahma-saṃsparśa. Śaṅkara: ब्रह्मसंस्पर्शम् — contact with brahman, which for the realised is non-different from being brahman.",
  '6.29': "He whose self is yoked by yoga sees the Self in all beings and all beings in the Self — he sees the same everywhere. Śaṅkara: सर्वभूतस्थम् आत्मानम् — this is one of his definitive Advaita-darśana texts; sameness because of identity, not because of similarity.",
  '6.30': "He who sees me everywhere and everything in me — I am not lost to him, nor he to me. Śaṅkara: न प्रणश्यामि — the bond is non-difference; mutual loss is impossible because there is no separation in the first place.",
  '6.31': "He who, established in unity, worships me dwelling in all beings — that yogī, however he acts, abides in me. Śaṅkara: सर्वथा वर्तमानोऽपि — whatever the externals look like, the inner identity guarantees the abidance.",
  '6.32': "He who, by analogy with himself, sees the same in all — pleasure and pain — he is the supreme yogī. Śaṅkara: आत्मौपम्येन — by self-analogy; the practical ethic of Advaita falls out as a natural consequence of the ontological insight.",
  '6.33': "Arjuna asks: this yoga of equanimity that you have spoken — I do not see its stable foundation in me, due to my restless mind. Śaṅkara: the disciple's honesty produces the chapter's last great section; the question is the precondition for the answer.",
  '6.34': "The mind is restless, turbulent, strong, hard — its restraint is hard like that of the wind. Śaṅkara: वायोरिव सुदुष्करम् — the simile concedes the difficulty; the bhāṣya does not minimise it.",
  '6.35': "Krishna replies: undoubtedly the mind is hard to restrain — but by abhyāsa and vairāgya it can be. Śaṅkara: अभ्यासेन च वैराग्येण च — these are the standard yoga-pair; both are required, neither alone suffices.",
  '6.36': "Yoga is hard to attain by the unrestrained self; for the controlled self striving rightly, it can be reached by the prescribed means. Śaṅkara: यतता शक्यः — effort succeeds when applied along the right lines; the verse refuses both fatalism and casualness.",
  '6.37': "Arjuna asks: what becomes of the failed yogī — fallen from yoga, does he not perish like a riven cloud? Śaṅkara: a serious question, for if yogic effort is wasted, the rationality of the path is undermined; the answer (6.38–45) is one of the Gītā's most consoling passages.",
  '6.38': "Does he not, fallen from both, deluded on the brahma-path, perish like a torn cloud, with no support? Śaṅkara: छिन्नाभ्र-iva — the simile invokes seeming total loss; the verse sets up the negation that follows.",
  '6.39': "Krishna alone can dispel this doubt — there is no other able to remove it. Śaṅkara: त्वम् एव — the disciple correctly identifies the right authority; only the Lord (or Self-knowledge) settles ultimate questions.",
  '6.40': "Krishna: neither here nor hereafter is he ruined; for one who does good comes to no evil end, son. Śaṅkara: न दुर्गतिम् तात गच्छति — the affectionate तात; the assurance is doctrinal — śubha-kṛt cannot end in durgati.",
  '6.41': "Reaching the world of those of meritorious deeds, dwelling there for years, the fallen yogī takes birth in a pure prosperous house. Śaṅkara: śuci-śrīmatāṃ gehe — favourable rebirth that allows continuation of the practice.",
  '6.42': "Or else he is born into a family of wise yogīs — such a birth is even more rare in this world. Śaṅkara: योगिनां कुले — exceedingly rare; the doctrine of pratiprasava-via-rebirth supports continuity of sādhana across lives.",
  '6.43': "There he regains the buddhi-saṃyoga of his former body and strives again for siddhi. Śaṅkara: पौर्वदेहिकम् बुद्धि-संयोगम् — saṃskāras transmit; nothing genuinely earned spiritually is lost.",
  '6.44': "Even unwillingly, he is carried by his prior practice; even an inquirer into yoga goes beyond the śabda-brahman. Śaṅkara: जिज्ञासुरपि — even the mere seeker exceeds Veda's ritual portion; jijñāsā itself is already above karma-kāṇḍa.",
  '6.45': "Striving with effort, the yogī, purified of sins, perfected over many births, reaches the supreme goal. Śaṅkara: अनेकजन्म-संसिद्धः — many lives may be needed; mokṣa is certain but timing is not promised.",
  '6.46': "The yogī is greater than tapasvīs, greater than ज्ञानीs (here, scholars), greater than karmīs — therefore be a yogī, Arjuna. Śaṅkara: he reads the ज्ञानी here as scholar (vidvān) of śāstra-knowledge, not the realised brahma-jñānin (whom no one is greater than); the yogī here is the meditator on the way to ज्ञान, hence his rank between karmin and brahma-jñānin.",
  '6.47': "Of all yogīs, he who, with inner self yoked to me, full of faith, worships me — I consider him most yoked. Śaṅkara: मद्गत-अन्तरात्मा — whose inmost self has gone to me; the highest yogī is the one whose identification has fully migrated to the Self/Lord, the bridge into chapter 7's bhakti-jñāna fusion."
};
